## 3. How the Platform Works

### The tenant model

```
SuperAdmin (you)
    │
    ├── Agency 1 (e.g. "Ravi's Digital")
    │       ├── Owner: ravi@ravisdgital.com
    │       ├── Employees: 5 people
    │       ├── Clients: 12 companies
    │       └── Active modules: M1, M2, M3, M4
    │
    ├── Agency 2 (e.g. "Spark Media")
    │       ├── Owner: priya@sparkmedia.in
    │       ├── Employees: 8 people
    │       ├── Clients: 20 companies
    │       └── Active modules: M1, M2, M3, M5, M6, M7
    │
    └── Agency 3 ...
```

Every row in every table has an `agency_id` foreign key. Every API endpoint checks `current_user.agency_id` before returning data. An owner at Agency 1 physically cannot see Agency 2's data even if they know the UUID — the query always filters by their agency ID.

### The module model

Modules are activated per-agency in the `agency_modules` table. A module toggle takes effect instantly — no deployment, no code change.

```sql
-- What activating M3 for an agency looks like:
INSERT INTO agency_modules (agency_id, module_code, is_active, activated_at)
VALUES ('agency-uuid', 'M3', true, now());
```

Every M3 endpoint has `require_module("M3")` as a FastAPI dependency. If `is_active = false`, every M3 request returns `403 Forbidden`. If `is_active = true`, they pass through.

### The event flow

```
External event (HubSpot deal, Gmail reply, WhatsApp message)
        │
        ▼
    n8n (webhook router)
        │
        ▼
    FastAPI endpoint
        │
        ├── Writes to PostgreSQL
        ├── May trigger Celery task
        └── May trigger LangGraph agent
                │
                ▼
            Claude API
                │
                ▼
            Action taken (email sent, alert raised, score saved)
```

